{"key":"post-13251781","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13251781</id>\n<content>You're correct about too wet or too dry ruining performance.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Cakes made a bit on the dry side will colonize faster, but will need extra water to fruit properly.&amp;nbsp; Cakes made on the 'slightly' wet side will colonize slower, but usually have enough moisture for first flush.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The best of both worlds is to make the cakes slightly dry, and then soak for 12 to 24 hours before first flush, otherwise known as dunk and roll.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;By using a ratio of one part brown rice flour or rice bran, one part water and two parts fine vermiculite, your mix will be slightly dry.&amp;nbsp; I'd suggest this mix.&amp;nbsp; If you're using course or medium vermiculite, you might need to use a bit more to keep the mix from being too wet.&amp;nbsp; I'd suggest following the procedure shown in the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/BRF-Pf-Tek&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;brf tek video&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp; Note the consistency of the mix, and try to duplicate that.&amp;nbsp; It's perfect.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>13251500</prev>\n<first>13250768</first>\n<last>13251781</last>\n<when>1285564086</when>\n<utime>09/27/10 08:08 AM</utime>\n</post>"}